restrictive lung diseases are conditions that impair ventilation without primary involvement of the lung parenchyma. These can be divided into neuromuscular disorders, chest wall disorders, and pleural diseases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a classic example of a neuromuscular disorder causing extrinsic restriction. It affects respiratory function through weakness of the diaphragm and intercostal muscles, leading to reduced lung volumes without intrinsic lung disease. Respiratory failure occurs in approximately 30% of cases and may require mechanical ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is an intrinsic restrictive lung disease characterised by scarring of the lung parenchyma. It directly affects the lung tissue rather than external mechanisms of breathing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is also an intrinsic lung disease involving granulomatous inflammation of the lung tissue and other organs. While it can cause restriction, it does so through direct lung involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumoconiosis\u003C/strong\u003E represents various dust-induced lung diseases that cause intrinsic restriction through direct damage to lung tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchiectasis\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily an obstructive airway disease characterised by permanent dilation of bronchi. It is neither intrinsic nor extrinsic restriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther examples of extrinsic restrictive lung diseases include myasthenia gravis (neuromuscular), kyphoscoliosis (chest wall), and pleural effusion (pleural disease).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neuromuscular disorders affecting respiratory muscles are classified as extrinsic lung diseases as they affect breathing mechanics without primary lung pathology.","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome can cause respiratory failure through ascending paralysis affecting the diaphragm and intercostal muscles.","Kyphoscoliosis is a chest wall deformity that can restrict lung expansion, classified as an extrinsic restrictive lung disease."],"references":["Bellanti R, Rinaldi S. Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome: a comprehensive review. Eur J Neurol. 2024 Aug;31(8):e16365. doi: 10.1111/ene.16365. Epub 2024 May 30. PMID: 38813755; PMCID: PMC11235944.","Nguyen TP, Taylor RS. Guillain-Barre Syndrome. 2023 Feb 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30335287.","Orlikowski D, Prigent H, Sharshar T, Lofaso F, Raphael JC. Respiratory dysfunction in Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome. Neurocrit Care. 2004;1(4):415-22. doi: 10.1385/NCC:1:4:415. PMID: 16174943.","Green C, Baker T, Subramaniam A. Predictors of respiratory failure in patients with Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Med J Aust. 2018 Mar 5;208(4):181-188. doi: 10.5694/mja17.00552. PMID: 29490222."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47065"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15495"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47065"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T23:23:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T23:24:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8186"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61612"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com